y Editions.\n*{{cite book | last=Stevenson | first= John James | year=1909 | title= A restoration of the Mausoleum at Halicarnassus | publisher= B. T. Batsford | place=London | url= https://archive.org/details/restorationofmau00stevrich }}\n*Wiater, Nicolas. 2011. ''The Ideology of Classicism: Language, History, and Identity In Dionysius of Halicarnassus''. New York: De Gruyter.\n*Winter, Frederick E. 2006. ''Studies In Hellenistic Architecture''. Toronto: University of Toronto Press.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=yes |others=yes |about=yes |label=Halicarnassus\n  |viaf= |lccn= |lcheading= |wikititle= }}\n*[http://www.livius.org Livius], [https://www.livius.org/ha-hd/halicarnassus/halicarnassus.html Halicarnassus] by Jona Lendering.\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Turkey/_Periods/Greek/_Texts/LETGKB/Mausoleum*.html The Tomb of Mausolus] W.&nbsp;R.&nbsp;Lethaby's reconstruction of the Mausoleum, 1908.\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Mausoleum.html Mausoleum] Article from Smith's Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities, 1875.\n\n{{Ancient settlements in Turkey}}\n\n[[Category:Ancient Greek archaeological sites in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Bodrum]]\n[[Category:Catholic titular sees in Asia]]\n[[Category:Doric Hexapolis]]\n[[Category:Greek colonies in Caria]]\n[[Category:Populated places in ancient Caria]]\n[[Category:History of Mu\u011fla Province]]\n[[Category:Achaemenid cities]]\n[[Category:Halicarnassus| ]]\n[[Category:Members of the Delian League]]\n\n[[he:\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05e8\u05d5\u05dd#\u05d4\u05dc\u05d9\u05e7\u05e8\u05e0\u05e1\u05d5\u05e1]]\n[[sk:Bodrum]]\n", "name_user": "Ozay of Halicarnassos", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halicarnassus"}
{"title_page": "Donna Air", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name        = Donna Air\n| image       = Donna Air, London, 2013 (crop).jpg\n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = Donna Air in 2013\n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1979|8|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Wallsend]], [[North Tyneside]], England\n| othername   = \n| occupation  = Actress, television presenter\n| yearsactive = \n| URL         = {{url|donnaair.com}}\n| partner     = {{Unbulleted list|\n*[[Damian Aspinall]] (2000\u20132007)\n*[[James Middleton (British businessman)|James Middleton]] (2013\u20132018)\n}}\n| children    = 1\n| awards      = \n}}\n'''Donna Marie Theresa Air''' (born 2 August 1979) is an English actress, television presenter and media personality.\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nDonna Marie Theresa Air was born on 2 August 1979,<ref name=Scotsman>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle-2-15039/hot-air-1-542316|title =Hot Air |newspaper= The Scotsman|date =4 August 2004 |accessdate=9 February 2020 |first=|last=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2000/nov/05/uknews.theobserver|title=Flawless, but hardly clueless|newspaper= The Observer|date =5 November 2000 | accessdate =9 February 2020 |first=Euan|last=Ferguson}}</ref> in [[Wallsend]], [[North Tyneside]], to receptionist Marie (n\u00e9e Lackenby) and mechanical engineer Trevor Air. The eldest of three children, Air has a sister, Francesca, and brother, Alexander.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/donna-airs-sister-speaks-childhood-1367207|title=Donna Air's sister speaks about their childhood |newspaper= Chronicle Live|date = 25 February 2013 | accessdate = 5 February 2020 |first=Kate|last=Procter}}</ref> Air grew up in [[Gosforth]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/donna-air-interview-a-security-guard-shouted-at-me-to-sit-down-the-next-thing-i-knew-i-was-being-carted-off-to-a-cell-ms6mhxb93|title=Donna Air interview: 'A security guard shouted at me to sit down. The next thing I knew, I was being carted off to a cell'|newspaper=The Times|date=9 February 2020|accessdate=9 February 2020 |first=Kirsty|last=Nutkins}}</ref> where she attended St Oswald's Catholic Primary School and later [[Sacred Heart Catholic High School, Newcastle upon Tyne|Sacred Heart Convent School]]. Air was then educated at [[Gosforth Academy|Gosforth High School]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/tm_objectid=15602124&method=full&siteid=50081-name_page.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100628043624/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/tm_objectid%3D15602124%26method%3Dfull%26siteid%3D50081-name_page.html | archivedate = 28 June 2010 | newspaper = Chronicle Live | title = Geordie girl stars | date = 7 June 2005 | accessdate = 24 June 2016 | first = Beth | last = Neil | url-status = dead }}</ref> and also attended First Act Theatre, a local youth theatre group. Her fellow students at First Act Theatre included [[Jill Halfpenny]] and [[Anthony McPartlin]]. Air also modeled as a child, appearing in ads for [[Nissan]], [[Asda]] and [[Lenor]].<ref name=Scotsman/>\n\nFirst appearing as an extra on [[CBBC]] programme ''[[Byker Grove]]'' aged 10, Air was asked to audition for a role by a producer, and was subsequently cast as Charlie Charlton. In 1994, Air and her co-stars Jayni Hoy and Vicky Taylor formed Byker Groove!,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/donna-air-crush-album-jellyhead-14476519 | title = Blast from pop past for Donna Air as album she recorded 22 years ago appears on iTunes |newspaper= Chronicle Live|date = 30 March 2018 | accessdate = 4 February 2020 |first=Simon|last= Duke}}</ref> releasing the single \"Love Your Sexy\", which charted at 48 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/31033/byker-grooove!/| publisher = Official Charts Company | title= BYKER GROOOVE!| accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> Air moved to London aged 15,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tatler.com/article/donna-air-the-split| publisher=Tatler |title= Donna Air opens up about being single at 40|last=Lawlor|first=Danielle|date=4 February 2020|accessdate= 5 February 2020}}</ref> subsequently becoming part of pop duo [[Crush (British band)|Crush]] with Jayni Hoy. Two of the band's singles released in 1996, \"Jellyhead\" and \"Luv'd Up\", charted in the UK at 50 and 45 respectively, while their debut studio album ''Teenage Kicks'' failed to chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/947/crush/|publisher= Official Charts Company |title= CRUSH|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The band's management team booked Crush on a tour of the United States, Japan and [[South East Asia]], commencing after Air completed her [[GCSEs]], with \"Jellyhead\" subsequently peaking at 76 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1996-12-21|title=Billboard Hot 100 for week of December 21, 1996|last=|first=|date=|website=Billboard|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her promotional touring, she returned to the United Kingdom and in September 1997 signed to [[MTV (UK and Ireland)|MTV UK]] to host the daily live show, ''[[MTV Select]]'',<ref name=DS>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a602/donna-air-leaves-mtv/|title=Donna Air leaves MTV|last=Wilkes|first=Neil|date=17 April 2000|website=Digital Spy|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref> later becoming a presenter of several shows including ''[[The Big Breakfast]]'', [[Channel 4]]'s flagship morning entertainment show. Air departed ''MTV Select'' in April 2000, citing her desire to return to acting and to devote more time to her role on ''The Big Breakfast'' as the reasons for her departure.<ref name=DS/> In January 2001, Air was promoted to a main presenter on ''The Big Breakfast'' in a relaunch of the programme amid falling viewer figures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1130716.stm|title=New faces at Big Breakfast|last=|first=|date=22 January 2001|website=BBC|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref> However, Air later resigned in May of that year,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a2861/donna-air-leaves-big-breakfast/|title=Donna Air leaves Big Breakfast|last=Wilkes|first=Neil|date=14 May 2001|website=Digital Spy|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref> with Channel 4 axing ''The Big Breakfast'' shortly thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1396854.stm|title=Big Breakfast washed up|last=|first=|date=19 June 2001|website=BBC|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref> Also in May, Air appeared in ''[[The Mummy Returns]]'', the sequel to ''[[The Mummy (1999 film)|The Mummy]]'' (1999), in a \"blink-and-you'll-miss-it cameo\" that BBC film critic Neil Smith described as one of the only points of difference between the sequel and the original film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1334280.stm|title=Recycled return for Mummy|last=Smith|first=Neil|date=18 May 2001|website=BBC|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nShe has also appeared in many television dramas, most recently ''[[Hollyoaks]]'' and ''[[Hotel Babylon]]'', [[BBC Television|BBC TV]] comedy ''[[Operation Good Guys]]'', [[Catherine Cookson]]'s six-parter ''A Dinner of Herbs'', and [[Lynda La Plante]]'s ''[[Supply & Demand (TV series)|Supply & Demand]]''. Air appeared in the films ''[[Still Crazy]]'' (1998) and ''[[Bad Day (film)|Bad Day]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/donna-air-im-more-confident-now-30374251.html |title=Donna Air: I'm more confident now | newspaper = [[The Belfast Telegraph]] |date=22 June 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> amongst others. Air presented on ''[[Channel 5 (UK)|Five]]'s'' early evening, magazine programme ''[[Live from Studio Five]]'', alongside regular presenter of the programme, [[Kate Walsh (presenter)|Kate Walsh]].\n\nIn January 2013, Air participated in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] programme, ''[[Splash! (TV series)|Splash!]]'' She replaced [[Jennifer Metcalfe]] at short notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tellymix.co.uk/reality-tv/129023-donna-air-replaces-jennifer-metcalfe-in-splash-heat-three-line-up.html |title=Donna Air replaces Jennifer Metcalfe in Splash! heat three line-up  |publisher=Tellymix.co.uk |date=9 February 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> In November 2017, Air announced that she would be taking part in the [[Dancing on Ice (series 10)|tenth series]] of ''[[Dancing on Ice]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Byker Groove. Donna Air confirmed for Dancing on Ice|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2017/1103/917195-dancing-on-ice-alex-beresford/|website=rte.ie|accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref> She was partnered with [[Mark Hanretty]]. They were eliminated in Week 7.\n\nIn 2019, Air was announced as having a starring role in the second series of the drama ''[[The Split (TV series)|The Split]]'', which started airing on [[BBC One]] in February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2019/the-split-s2|title=BBC - Second series of Abi Morgan\u2019s original BBC One drama The Split begins production - Media Centre|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2000, Air met businessman and animal conservationist [[Damian Aspinall]], having been introduced by their mutual friend [[Tara Palmer-Tomkinson]].<ref name=TDT>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2018/01/06/donna-air-private-romance-james-middleton-happy/|title=Donna Air on her very private romance with James Middleton: 'I\u2019m very happy'|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last=Gannon|first=Louise|date=6 January 2018|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> The pair began a long-term relationship, with Air giving birth to their daughter, Freya Air Aspinall, in September 2003.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/3258811.stm |title=TV star's baby handed to gorillas|publisher=BBC News |date=10 November 2003 |accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref> Shortly after her birth the couple announced their intention to place their baby daughter in the care of a gorilla, a ritual in which Aspinall's older children had already taken part.<ref name=BBC/> Air and Aspinall separated amicably in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/donna-air-splits-from-40m-zoo-tycoon-6596163.html|title=Donna Air splits from \u00a340m zoo tycoon|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=8 July 2007 |accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> In 2013, Air began dating [[James Middleton (British businessman)|James Middleton]], the younger brother of [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]];<ref name=TDT/> the pair eventually separated in 2018.<ref name=MOS>{{cite news|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2018021946418/donna-air-confirms-split-james-middleton/|title=Donna Air confirms split from James Middleton|publisher=Hello!|date=19 February 2018 |accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> Air lives in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]], London.<ref name=ES>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/my-london-donna-air-a4274691.html|title=My London: Donna Air|newspaper=[[Evening Standard]]|last=MacBain|first=Hamish|date=30 October 2019|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nAir supports the [[Macmillan Cancer Support]], [[Race for Life]], [[Sport Relief]] and [[Jeans for Genes]] charities.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.demotix.com/news/2780697/macmillan-delonghi-art-auction-2013-raised-money-cancer-support | title = Macmillan De'Longhi Art Auction 2013 raised money for Cancer Support | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150102051153/http://www.demotix.com/news/2780697/macmillan-delonghi-art-auction-2013-raised-money-cancer-support#media-2780027 | archivedate = 2 January 2015 | date = 23 September 2013 | first = Eugenie | last = Absalom | publisher = [[Demotix]] }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Still Crazy]]''\n| Dutch Hitch-Hiker\n| \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Truth or Dare''\n| Louise\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Mummy Returns]]''\n| Show Girl\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The One and Only (2002 film)|The One & Only]]''\n| Donna\n| \n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Bad Day (film)|Bad Day]]''\n| Abby Barrett\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Counselor]]''\n| Chauffeur\n| \n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Age of Kill]]''\n| Sarah Blake\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1992-1995\n| ''[[Byker Grove]]''\n| Charlie Charlton\n| 4 series\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Supply & Demand (TV series)|Supply & Demand]]''\n| Lucy\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''A Dinner of Herbs''\n| Maggie Roystan\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Breeze Block (TV series)|Breeze Block]]''\n| Kiki\n| Miniseries\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Hotel Babylon]]''\n| Rachel\n| One episode\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Hollyoaks]]''\n| Sophia\n| One episode\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[The Split (TV series)|The Split]]''\n| Fi Hansen\n| 6 episodes\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0014756|name=Donna Air}}\n*{{official website|http://www.donnaair.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Air, Donna}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:People from Gosforth]]\n[[Category:People from Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gosforth Academy]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:English media personalities]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name        = Donna Air\n| image       = Donna Air, London, 2013 (crop).jpg\n| imagesize   =\n| caption     = Donna Air in 2013\n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1979|8|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Wallsend]], [[North Tyneside]], England\n| othername   = \n| occupation  = Actress, television presenter\n| yearsactive = \n| URL         = {{url|donnaair.com}}\n| partner     = {{Unbulleted list|\n*[[Damian Aspinall]] (2000\u20132007)\n*[[James Middleton (British businessman)|James Middleton]] (2013\u20132018)\n}}\n| children    = 1\n| awards      = \n}}\n'''Donna Marie Theresa Air''' (born 2 August 1979) is an English actress, television presenter and media personality.\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nDonna Marie Theresa Air was born on 2 August 1979,<ref name=Scotsman>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle-2-15039/hot-air-1-542316|title =Hot Air |newspaper= The Scotsman|date =4 August 2004 |accessdate=9 February 2020 |first=|last=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2000/nov/05/uknews.theobserver|title=Flawless, but hardly clueless|newspaper= The Observer|date =5 November 2000 | accessdate =9 February 2020 |first=Euan|last=Ferguson}}</ref> in [[Wallsend]], [[North Tyneside]], to receptionist Marie (n\u00e9e Lackenby) and mechanical engineer Trevor Air. The eldest of three children, Air has a sister, Francesca, and brother, Alexander.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/donna-airs-sister-speaks-childhood-1367207|title=Donna Air's sister speaks about their childhood |newspaper= Chronicle Live|date = 25 February 2013 | accessdate = 5 February 2020 |first=Kate|last=Procter}}</ref> Air grew up in [[Gosforth]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/donna-air-interview-a-security-guard-shouted-at-me-to-sit-down-the-next-thing-i-knew-i-was-being-carted-off-to-a-cell-ms6mhxb93|title=Donna Air interview: 'A security guard shouted at me to sit down. The next thing I knew, I was being carted off to a cell'|newspaper=The Times|date=9 February 2020|accessdate=9 February 2020 |first=Kirsty|last=Nutkins}}</ref> where she attended St Oswald's Catholic Primary School and later [[Sacred Heart Catholic High School, Newcastle upon Tyne|Sacred Heart Convent School]]. Air was then educated at [[Gosforth Academy|Gosforth High School]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/tm_objectid=15602124&method=full&siteid=50081-name_page.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100628043624/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/tm_objectid%3D15602124%26method%3Dfull%26siteid%3D50081-name_page.html | archivedate = 28 June 2010 | newspaper = Chronicle Live | title = Geordie girl stars | date = 7 June 2005 | accessdate = 24 June 2016 | first = Beth | last = Neil | url-status = dead }}</ref> and also attended First Act Theatre, a local youth theatre group. Her fellow students at First Act Theatre included [[Jill Halfpenny]] and [[Anthony McPartlin]]. Air also modeled as a child, appearing in ads for [[Nissan]], [[Asda]] and [[Lenor]].<ref name=Scotsman/>\n\nFirst appearing as an extra on [[CBBC]] programme ''[[Byker Grove]]'' aged 10, Air was asked to audition for a role by a producer, and was subsequently cast as Charlie Charlton. In 1994, Air and her co-stars Jayni Hoy and Vicky Taylor formed Byker Groove!,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/donna-air-crush-album-jellyhead-14476519 | title = Blast from pop past for Donna Air as album she recorded 22 years ago appears on iTunes |newspaper= Chronicle Live|date = 30 March 2018 | accessdate = 4 February 2020 |first=Simon|last= Duke}}</ref> releasing the single \"Love Your Sexy\", which charted at 48 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/31033/byker-grooove!/| publisher = Official Charts Company | title= BYKER GROOOVE!| accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> Air moved to London aged 15,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tatler.com/article/donna-air-the-split| publisher=Tatler |title= Donna Air opens up about being single at 40|last=Lawlor|first=Danielle|date=4 February 2020|accessdate= 5 February 2020}}</ref> subsequently becoming part of pop duo [[Crush (British band)|Crush]] with Jayni Hoy. Two of the band's singles released in 1996, \"Jellyhead\" and \"Luv'd Up\", charted in the UK at 50 and 45 respectively, while their debut studio album ''Teenage Kicks'' failed to chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/947/crush/|publisher= Official Charts Company |title= CRUSH|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The band's management team booked Crush on a tour of the United States, Japan and [[South East Asia]], commencing after Air completed her [[GCSEs]], with \"Jellyhead\" subsequently peaking at 76 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100/1996-12-21|title=Billboard Hot 100 for week of December 21, 1996|last=|first=|date=|website=Billboard|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her promotional touring, she returned to the United Kingdom and in September 1997 signed to [[MTV (UK and Ireland)|MTV UK]] to host the daily live show, ''[[MTV Select]]'',<ref name=DS>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a602/donna-air-leaves-mtv/|title=Donna Air leaves MTV|last=Wilkes|first=Neil|date=17 April 2000|website=Digital Spy|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref> later becoming a presenter of several shows including ''[[The Big Breakfast]]'', [[Channel 4]]'s flagship morning entertainment show. Air departed ''MTV Select'' in April 2000, citing her desire to return to acting and to devote more time to her role on ''The Big Breakfast'' as the reasons for her departure.<ref name=DS/> In January 2001, Air was promoted to a main presenter on ''The Big Breakfast'' in a relaunch of the programme amid falling viewer figures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1130716.stm|title=New faces at Big Breakfast|last=|first=|date=22 January 2001|website=BBC|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref> However, Air later resigned in May of that year,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a2861/donna-air-leaves-big-breakfast/|title=Donna Air leaves Big Breakfast|last=Wilkes|first=Neil|date=14 May 2001|website=Digital Spy|access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref> with Channel 4 axing ''The Big Breakfast'' shortly thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1396854.stm|title=Big Breakfast washed up|last=|first=|date=19 June 2001|website=BBC|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref> Also in May, Air appeared in ''[[The Mummy Returns]]'', the sequel to ''[[The Mummy (1999 film)|The Mummy]]'' (1999), in a \"blink-and-you'll-miss-it cameo\" that BBC film critic Neil Smith described as one of the only points of difference between the sequel and the original film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1334280.stm|title=Recycled return for Mummy|last=Smith|first=Neil|date=18 May 2001|website=BBC|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nShe has also appeared in many television dramas, most recently ''[[Hollyoaks]]'' and ''[[Hotel Babylon]]'', [[BBC Television|BBC TV]] comedy ''[[Operation Good Guys]]'', [[Catherine Cookson]]'s six-parter ''A Dinner of Herbs'', and [[Lynda La Plante]]'s ''[[Supply & Demand (TV series)|Supply & Demand]]''. Air appeared in the films ''[[Still Crazy]]'' (1998) and ''[[Bad Day (film)|Bad Day]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/donna-air-im-more-confident-now-30374251.html |title=Donna Air: I'm more confident now | newspaper = [[The Belfast Telegraph]] |date=22 June 2014 |accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> amongst others. Air presented on ''[[Channel 5 (UK)|Five]]'s'' early evening, magazine programme ''[[Live from Studio Five]]'', alongside regular presenter of the programme, [[Kate Walsh (presenter)|Kate Walsh]].\n\nIn January 2013, Air participated in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] programme, ''[[Splash! (TV series)|Splash!]]'' She replaced [[Jennifer Metcalfe]] at short notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tellymix.co.uk/reality-tv/129023-donna-air-replaces-jennifer-metcalfe-in-splash-heat-three-line-up.html |title=Donna Air replaces Jennifer Metcalfe in Splash! heat three line-up  |publisher=Tellymix.co.uk |date=9 February 2013 |accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> In November 2017, Air announced that she would be taking part in the [[Dancing on Ice (series 10)|tenth series]] of ''[[Dancing on Ice]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Byker Groove. Donna Air confirmed for Dancing on Ice|url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2017/1103/917195-dancing-on-ice-alex-beresford/|website=rte.ie|accessdate=4 November 2017}}</ref> She was partnered with [[Mark Hanretty]]. They were eliminated in Week 7.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2000, Air met businessman and animal conservationist [[Damian Aspinall]], having been introduced by their mutual friend [[Tara Palmer-Tomkinson]].<ref name=TDT>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2018/01/06/donna-air-private-romance-james-middleton-happy/|title=Donna Air on her very private romance with James Middleton: 'I\u2019m very happy'|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|last=Gannon|first=Louise|date=6 January 2018|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> The pair began a long-term relationship, with Air giving birth to their daughter, Freya Air Aspinall, in September 2003.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/kent/3258811.stm |title=TV star's baby handed to gorillas|publisher=BBC News |date=10 November 2003 |accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref> Shortly after her birth the couple announced their intention to place their baby daughter in the care of a gorilla, a ritual in which Aspinall's older children had already taken part.<ref name=BBC/> Air and Aspinall separated amicably in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/donna-air-splits-from-40m-zoo-tycoon-6596163.html|title=Donna Air splits from \u00a340m zoo tycoon|newspaper=[[London Evening Standard]]|date=8 July 2007 |accessdate=1 May 2015}}</ref> In 2013, Air began dating [[James Middleton (British businessman)|James Middleton]], the younger brother of [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]];<ref name=TDT/> the pair eventually separated in 2018.<ref name=MOS>{{cite news|url=https://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2018021946418/donna-air-confirms-split-james-middleton/|title=Donna Air confirms split from James Middleton|publisher=Hello!|date=19 February 2018 |accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> Air lives in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]], London.<ref name=ES>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/my-london-donna-air-a4274691.html|title=My London: Donna Air|newspaper=[[Evening Standard]]|last=MacBain|first=Hamish|date=30 October 2019|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nAir supports the [[Macmillan Cancer Support]], [[Race for Life]], [[Sport Relief]] and [[Jeans for Genes]] charities.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.demotix.com/news/2780697/macmillan-delonghi-art-auction-2013-raised-money-cancer-support | title = Macmillan De'Longhi Art Auction 2013 raised money for Cancer Support | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150102051153/http://www.demotix.com/news/2780697/macmillan-delonghi-art-auction-2013-raised-money-cancer-support#media-2780027 | archivedate = 2 January 2015 | date = 23 September 2013 | first = Eugenie | last = Absalom | publisher = [[Demotix]] }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Still Crazy]]''\n| Dutch Hitch-Hiker\n| \n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Truth or Dare''\n| Louise\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Mummy Returns]]''\n| Show Girl\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The One and Only (2002 film)|The One & Only]]''\n| Donna\n| \n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Bad Day (film)|Bad Day]]''\n| Abby Barre